<P>Becau&s;e he was fond of peace, and &s;eemed to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ave the intere&s;t of his people at heart. He had no am|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ition to extend his power, except by treaties and by wi&s;|dom; and his great plan was, to equalize the people, by <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">epre&s;&s;ing the nobility and clergy and giving the popu|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ace more weight in the &s;cale of government; but, his greate&s;t efforts were to promote trade and commerce. He <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ied at the age of fifty-two, having reigned twenty-three years.</P>
<P>In Henry VIII. his &s;on and &s;ucce&s;&s;or, all factions were <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">xtingui&s;hed, and all divi&s;ions united. By the father's <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">de he claimed the crown, from the hou&s;e of Lanca&s;ter; by the mother's from the hou&s;e of York: and his father <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">eft him a kingdom in peace, prudent mini&s;ters, and a full trea&s;ury.</P>
