<P>He permits evil, to draw from it a greater <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">d. If he afflicts good men in this life, it is to re|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">d their virtues in another. If he gives the wicked <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters">&s;itory pro&s;perity, he makes u&s;e of their malice, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">er to exerci&s;e his ju&s;tice or his mercy upon his <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">tures. Such is, my friend, the idea which God given us of him&s;elf and of his attributes.</P>
