<SP>
<SPEAKER>ERAST.</SPEAKER>
<P>Water-&s;pouts are a great quantity of water drawn up into the air, by the attraction of a low cloud, which &s;eems to de&s;cend for that purpo&s;e; at a di&s;tance it appears like a large funnel, the &s;mall end touching the &s;ea, the broad end enveloped in the clouds. Under the &s;mall end the water bubbles up, and appears to boil. Was a &s;hip to run foul of one of the&s;e &s;pouts, the waters would break, deluge the ve&s;&s;el, and probably &s;ink it. Seamen generally fire a &s;hot at it when within reach, and thus di&s;per&s;e it, which the agitation of the air, by the explo&s;ion, &s;eldom fails to do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
