<P>The Cordeliers of Peru, in America, whi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> are a chain of mountains near 1500 leagues in length&punc; One of the&s;e is, perhaps, the highe&s;t mountain in t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> world. It reaches to the middle region of the air. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ummit is 9660 yards above the level of the &s;ea, nearly &s;ix miles in height. There are other mounta<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> not quite &s;o high. For example, Mount Sinai, in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">+pan; the Pike of Teneriffe, in Africa; Mount Ce<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> in the Alps; Mount Atlas, and many others: and, in ob&s;ervable, that we experience more cold in eleva<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">
<PB N="85" REF="166">places, particularly on the mountains, than in the val|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ies or plains.</P>
