<P>Becau&s;e the air is keener, and the &s;un's rays do not fall on them perpendicularly. It is thus we &s;ee the highe&s;t mountains almo&s;t always covered with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">now. The cold is &s;o exce&s;&s;ive at a certain height on the Cordeliers, that men and animals will freeze, and become as hard as &s;tone, without putrefying.</P>
